WEBVTT

00:00:00.010 --> 00:00:02.000
Hello.

00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:03.000
Thanks, Boris.

00:00:03.040 --> 00:00:05.620
It's so good to be here.

00:00:06.240 --> 00:00:08.610
It's also a lot, and I just want to take

00:00:08.880 --> 00:00:10.900
a beat to acknowledge that.

00:00:10.900 --> 00:00:14.260
There's so much devastating in the world right now, but

00:00:14.260 --> 00:00:17.750
in this room, there's so many inspiring people with inspiring

00:00:17.880 --> 00:00:18.790
ideas and dreams.

00:00:18.790 --> 00:00:22.080
Holding it all takes a lot of energy, and while it

00:00:22.090 --> 00:00:24.240
's exciting, I'm feeling overwhelmed, so I just want

00:00:24.280 --> 00:00:27.330
to share that and hold space if you're feeling overwhelmed,

00:00:27.340 --> 00:00:27.680
too.

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:28.410
I'm Blaine.

00:00:28.410 --> 00:00:30.980
I work at New Public, where I'm the engineering lead

00:00:30.980 --> 00:00:32.990
on a roundabout project, which we're building to help

00:00:33.300 --> 00:00:37.320
local neighborhoods come together online in a healthy way, without the

00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:40.960
noise or toxicity of big social media platforms.

00:00:40.960 --> 00:00:47.420
I'm here, like so many, after building for a

00:00:47.420 --> 00:00:54.640
lifetime online, and my past work as a founding engineer at

00:00:54.640 --> 00:00:55.790
Twitter and the creator of our auth.

00:00:55.800 --> 00:01:01.700
Speaking of neighborhoods, I'm honored to be here with you

00:01:01.700 --> 00:01:01.860
.

00:01:01.860 --> 00:01:02.540
Oh, sorry.

00:01:02.540 --> 00:01:04.370
No, no, I don't have slides.

00:01:04.380 --> 00:01:05.900
I'm just going to talk.

00:01:05.900 --> 00:01:10.180
I could put some slime molds or something up.

00:01:10.180 --> 00:01:11.230
Right.

00:01:11.230 --> 00:01:17.080
So speaking of neighborhoods, I'm honored to be here with

00:01:17.080 --> 00:01:20.400
you in Muskeman territory, bringing this talk from my

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:22.190
home in Sinai's territory.

00:01:22.260 --> 00:01:24.900
I grew up in BC, in the territories of the D

00:01:24.900 --> 00:01:26.710
ine, Simisen, Kitsumkalem, Tan

00:01:26.710 --> 00:01:28.650
aha, and Semiamu, and now the Sinai

00:01:28.650 --> 00:01:29.190
xt peoples.

00:01:29.360 --> 00:01:32.730
I moved around a lot, and I value immensely the broad

00:01:32.730 --> 00:01:34.620
perspective that this disruption gifted me.

00:01:34.620 --> 00:01:37.190
It also gave me a deep appreciation for the size and diversity

00:01:37.190 --> 00:01:39.890
of this province, and how much it resists being flatten

00:01:39.890 --> 00:01:40.650
ed into one story.

00:01:40.860 --> 00:01:43.900
If you have the chance while you're here, I really

00:01:43.900 --> 00:01:45.990
encourage you to go visit the Museum of Anthropology just

00:01:46.150 --> 00:01:46.650
across campus.

00:01:46.780 --> 00:01:49.060
It's one of the best places I know to encounter that

00:01:49.340 --> 00:01:50.760
diversity on its own terms.

00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:53.300
And it's special for me to share this with you from

00:01:53.300 --> 00:01:55.560
my bioregional neighborhood and my alma mater.

00:01:55.680 --> 00:01:58.130
I studied here, and this is actually where the thread of

00:01:58.130 --> 00:01:58.900
the talk begins.

00:01:58.940 --> 00:01:59.950
So at 9 a.

00:01:59.960 --> 00:02:00.130
m.

00:02:00.340 --> 00:02:05.060
on September 11th, 2001, I was attending a lecture

00:02:05.060 --> 00:02:08.500
on relational database theory inside the Hennings building at UBC

00:02:08.530 --> 00:02:09.610
, just over there.

00:02:09.610 --> 00:02:12.850
It's literally the next building over from where we are now

00:02:13.050 --> 00:02:13.180
.

00:02:13.180 --> 00:02:16.760
For the duration of that class, not the professor, not

00:02:16.850 --> 00:02:20.030
the students, no one addressed the elephant in the room.

00:02:20.240 --> 00:02:23.170
And looking around, I realized that the people in the room

00:02:23.170 --> 00:02:25.530
, the people who were being trained to build the software systems

00:02:25.750 --> 00:02:28.390
of the future, were not being trained to think about,

00:02:28.480 --> 00:02:31.500
think seriously about what those systems would do when they met actual

00:02:31.500 --> 00:02:32.080
humans.

00:02:32.080 --> 00:02:34.560
So, on 9-11, I switched my major from

00:02:34.560 --> 00:02:36.560
computer science to sociology.

00:02:36.560 --> 00:02:41.900
I realized that I could teach myself the software pieces, but

00:02:41.900 --> 00:02:44.960
that would leave me without a deeper understanding of the social systems

00:02:45.330 --> 00:02:46.810
that the technology was for.

00:02:46.810 --> 00:02:50.600
This wasn't a rejection of the technological systems.

00:02:50.600 --> 00:02:52.410
I like tech.

00:02:52.420 --> 00:02:56.230
It was a realization about what kind of approach is needed to

00:02:56.230 --> 00:02:59.380
build technological tools to support people and societies.

00:02:59.380 --> 00:03:05.370
Engineering trains you to specify desired behavior, build the system,

00:03:05.370 --> 00:03:07.260
and treat deviation as a bug.

00:03:07.260 --> 00:03:11.300
I believe this approach is incompatible with social software.

00:03:11.300 --> 00:03:14.140
Social systems are living, breathing things.

00:03:14.410 --> 00:03:16.810
Sociology, on the other hand, trains you to observe

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:19.870
what is actually happening, to identify the patterns, to try

00:03:19.870 --> 00:03:22.600
and understand what produces healthy outcomes.

00:03:22.600 --> 00:03:26.290
Only then can you cultivate those conditions.

00:03:26.360 --> 00:03:29.590
You don't define and control the system.

00:03:29.590 --> 00:03:30.190
You tend it.

00:03:30.400 --> 00:03:31.470
You steward it.

00:03:31.470 --> 00:03:36.810
That distinction between prescribing outcomes and describing conditions is central to

00:03:36.810 --> 00:03:39.980
understanding what it means to build the sort of software we want

00:03:39.980 --> 00:03:40.980
to see in the world.

00:03:41.120 --> 00:03:46.070
This is part of a long conversation, one that starts before

00:03:46.230 --> 00:03:49.430
Christopher Alexander's patterns and Ursula Franklin's warnings about pres

00:03:49.630 --> 00:03:52.880
criptive technologies and continues through resonant local first home-

00:03:52.880 --> 00:03:54.040
cooked software.

00:03:54.130 --> 00:03:57.840
Butler and Ostrom would be proud of today's intercommun

00:03:57.840 --> 00:03:59.270
al revolutionary networks.

00:03:59.300 --> 00:04:01.710
Many of you in this room and our peers elsewhere at the

00:04:01.750 --> 00:04:05.890
conference have signed manifestos, written code, and built organizations

00:04:05.890 --> 00:04:08.030
that embody versions of this argument.

00:04:08.030 --> 00:04:10.790
So I'm not here to convince you that the first era

00:04:10.920 --> 00:04:12.520
of social media got it wrong.

00:04:12.520 --> 00:04:13.620
You already know that.

00:04:14.430 --> 00:04:17.200
What I want to do is dig in a little and push

00:04:17.200 --> 00:04:19.330
us to think a little bit further.

00:04:19.650 --> 00:04:23.620
Because even in this community, in my own mind, I

00:04:23.620 --> 00:04:27.060
hear a lingering instinct, a quiet hope that the answer is

00:04:27.210 --> 00:04:30.270
something like, "a good trust and safety team, but

00:04:30.290 --> 00:04:33.770
decentralized, a better manager, a kinder machine." And

00:04:33.770 --> 00:04:36.140
I want to argue that the shift we need is more radical

00:04:36.140 --> 00:04:36.450
than that.

00:04:36.460 --> 00:04:38.820
And I want to ground it in something visceral.

00:04:38.820 --> 00:04:44.190
Something that I think proves that centralized cultural governance fails structurally

00:04:44.280 --> 00:04:45.620
, not just politically.

00:04:45.620 --> 00:04:47.820
It comes from cheese.

00:04:47.820 --> 00:04:53.190
A decade ago, when I was living in London, I

00:04:53.190 --> 00:04:55.800
encountered the work of Bronwyn Percival, who manages

00:04:55.820 --> 00:04:59.020
the cheese counter at Neal's Yard Dairy in

00:04:59.020 --> 00:05:02.160
London, and has written brilliantly about the relationship between safety

00:05:02.160 --> 00:05:04.290
, complexity, and living systems.

00:05:04.300 --> 00:05:07.610
She tells a story about traditional cheesemaking in the

00:05:07.610 --> 00:05:08.990
Overn region of France.

00:05:09.020 --> 00:05:14.130
They make raw milk cheeses made with unpasteurized

00:05:14.140 --> 00:05:17.280
milk, milked by hand, in open fields, on

00:05:17.280 --> 00:05:23.290
volcanic slopes, into wooden buckets in the fields that serve as

00:05:23.330 --> 00:05:25.900
the molds for the traditional wheels of Seller.

00:05:25.900 --> 00:05:29.330
From above the managerial stance, this looks like a food

00:05:29.370 --> 00:05:30.780
safety nightmare.

00:05:30.780 --> 00:05:34.490
There's no sterilization, there's no fully controlled environment

00:05:34.590 --> 00:05:35.750
, no standardized inputs.

00:05:35.780 --> 00:05:39.050
And yet, these cheeses can be remarkably resilient.

00:05:39.050 --> 00:05:40.060
Why?

00:05:40.390 --> 00:05:42.780
Because the microbial culture is already there.

00:05:42.780 --> 00:05:46.230
It has adapted over time to this place, this practice,

00:05:46.260 --> 00:05:47.660
this environment.

00:05:47.660 --> 00:05:51.110
It occupies the ecological niches that a harmful organism would

00:05:51.110 --> 00:05:52.630
otherwise move into.

00:05:52.660 --> 00:05:55.930
Safety does not come from absence.

00:05:55.930 --> 00:05:59.980
It comes from presence, from a healthy, adapted, living

00:05:59.980 --> 00:06:00.660
biome.

00:06:00.660 --> 00:06:04.040
And one of the remarkable things about traditional cheeses is that

00:06:04.040 --> 00:06:05.540
they are not all the same.

00:06:05.540 --> 00:06:08.250
They are shaped by geography, by farming practice, by the

00:06:08.300 --> 00:06:11.160
cave, by the shelf, the climate, the accumulated microb

00:06:11.370 --> 00:06:12.340
ial life of a place.

00:06:12.340 --> 00:06:14.970
Terroir is not just branding.

00:06:14.970 --> 00:06:17.320
It's microbial geography.

00:06:17.340 --> 00:06:21.340
It is a living community shaped by place over time.

00:06:21.340 --> 00:06:23.440
Now, pasteurization.

00:06:23.640 --> 00:06:25.620
Pasteurization saved lives.

00:06:25.620 --> 00:06:26.960
That needs to be said clearly.

00:06:27.020 --> 00:06:29.120
Milk-borne disease was real.

00:06:29.140 --> 00:06:34.250
Heating milk made industrial-scale dairy possible and dramatically reduced

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:34.740
risk.

00:06:34.740 --> 00:06:36.830
But it also wiped the site clean.

00:06:37.020 --> 00:06:41.710
It destroyed the indigenous microbial ecology, the living community that

00:06:41.740 --> 00:06:45.220
evolved over long periods of practice to do useful things.

00:06:45.220 --> 00:06:48.250
And then it added back a simplified starter culture.

00:06:48.260 --> 00:06:52.640
A few selected strains chosen for predictability produced by just two

00:06:52.870 --> 00:06:53.890
corporations globally.

00:06:54.060 --> 00:06:57.520
You get safe, you get consistent, you get scalable,

00:06:57.580 --> 00:06:58.620
and you lose flavor.

00:06:58.620 --> 00:07:00.500
However, you lose specificity.

00:07:00.540 --> 00:07:04.220
You lose 90% of the biological diversity, the accumulated intelligence

00:07:04.220 --> 00:07:08.060
of a living system adapted to its context, to our context

00:07:08.110 --> 00:07:08.470
.

00:07:08.500 --> 00:07:11.100
Sterilization didn't even fully eliminate the risk.

00:07:11.100 --> 00:07:13.100
Sterilization didn't even fully eliminate the risk.

00:07:13.100 --> 00:07:16.380
It relocated it from places where living systems could manage it

00:07:16.380 --> 00:07:19.380
to places where only procedural compliance could.

00:07:19.380 --> 00:07:23.110
Now, people aren't cheese.

00:07:23.260 --> 00:07:26.690
Human communities are infinitely more complex than 40 kilograms of microbial

00:07:26.690 --> 00:07:27.260
ecology.

00:07:27.260 --> 00:07:34.240
The required diversity in a healthy cultural system is structurally impossible

00:07:34.240 --> 00:07:36.980
to encode from one place at planetary scale.

00:07:36.980 --> 00:07:40.710
Not just difficult, not just politically fraught, structurally

00:07:41.540 --> 00:07:41.860
impossible.

00:07:41.860 --> 00:07:45.570
And that impossibility does not get better as you add complexity

00:07:45.570 --> 00:07:45.860
.

00:07:45.860 --> 00:07:46.830
It gets worse.

00:07:46.860 --> 00:07:50.560
If a single centralized approach can't preserve the diversity of cheese

00:07:50.560 --> 00:07:53.160
, one of the simplest living systems that we know how to

00:07:53.160 --> 00:07:57.740
cultivate, then consider what we attempted over the last 20 years

00:07:57.740 --> 00:07:58.740
with human culture.

00:07:58.740 --> 00:08:02.170
At most half a dozen global platforms, each one operating as

00:08:02.180 --> 00:08:06.060
a single cultural pasteurization plant for hundreds of millions of

00:08:06.060 --> 00:08:11.180
people, one classification scheme, one starter culture, one idea

00:08:11.220 --> 00:08:14.620
of what safe means, one interface for the entire world.

00:08:14.620 --> 00:08:19.310
The possible forms of healthy human community are orders of magnitude more

00:08:19.340 --> 00:08:21.490
complex than a cheese culture.

00:08:21.500 --> 00:08:26.480
They require correspondingly richer means of expression, richer and more

00:08:26.540 --> 00:08:30.540
diverse forms of self-governance, richer mechanisms for maintaining

00:08:30.540 --> 00:08:31.180
health.

00:08:31.180 --> 00:08:36.390
I think the first generation of the social web really did try

00:08:36.390 --> 00:08:39.100
to pasteurize human culture.

00:08:39.100 --> 00:08:43.210
And the thing that I want us to reckon with is not

00:08:43.630 --> 00:08:47.390
just that it failed, it is that it could not have

00:08:47.430 --> 00:08:48.670
succeeded.

00:08:48.700 --> 00:08:52.410
Not because the people involved were bad, not because the incentives

00:08:52.410 --> 00:08:57.310
were wrong, but because the architecture made it structurally impossible

00:08:57.420 --> 00:08:59.420
to preserve the thing that it was trying to protect.

00:08:59.420 --> 00:09:02.870
And not that it didn't do damage, it did enormous

00:09:02.870 --> 00:09:03.980
damage.

00:09:03.980 --> 00:09:07.430
But it could never have achieved what it set out to do

00:09:07.430 --> 00:09:12.260
because human culture is more resilient than any system designed to contain

00:09:12.260 --> 00:09:12.610
it.

00:09:12.620 --> 00:09:15.330
There are two ways to make something safe at scale.

00:09:15.580 --> 00:09:18.900
You can sterilize it or you can cultivate the conditions under

00:09:18.900 --> 00:09:20.690
which healthy life persists.

00:09:20.700 --> 00:09:23.840
The first era chose the first path, I think it's

00:09:23.840 --> 00:09:25.580
time to try the second.

00:09:25.580 --> 00:09:28.850
So what does the second path actually require?

00:09:28.860 --> 00:09:32.320
If you study living systems, cells, ecosystems, communities that

00:09:32.450 --> 00:09:35.390
persist over time, you notice they all solve the same problem

00:09:35.460 --> 00:09:35.460
.

00:09:35.660 --> 00:09:41.290
They maintain a difference between inside and outside.

00:09:41.580 --> 00:09:44.700
A cell does this with a membrane, not a wall,

00:09:44.700 --> 00:09:47.010
a membrane, selectively permeable.

00:09:47.020 --> 00:09:50.700
It lets certain things in and it keeps certain things out.

00:09:50.700 --> 00:09:53.890
And the specificity of what crosses that boundary is what makes

00:09:53.890 --> 00:09:56.780
the cell alive, rather than just chemicals in equilibrium with their

00:09:56.950 --> 00:09:57.230
surroundings.

00:09:57.340 --> 00:10:01.300
A community does this too, with norms, with shared context

00:10:01.300 --> 00:10:04.300
, with the slow accumulation of trust.

00:10:04.300 --> 00:10:07.290
When Rudy spoke of groundings with his siblings, this is

00:10:07.340 --> 00:10:08.700
what he's pointing to.

00:10:08.700 --> 00:10:14.260
A community that cannot maintain the difference from its environment is not

00:10:14.260 --> 00:10:16.940
really a community, it's just more environment.

00:10:16.940 --> 00:10:20.350
Aaron's example this morning of the numbness that results from

00:10:20.350 --> 00:10:23.260
the jarring contrast of the joy of a wedding and the

00:10:23.260 --> 00:10:26.910
horror of international atrocities is a poignant illustration of this

00:10:26.910 --> 00:10:27.050
.

00:10:27.100 --> 00:10:32.210
And this is what happened on the old platforms, the membrane

00:10:32.280 --> 00:10:36.520
dissolved, inside became outside, and every context collapsed into one

00:10:36.520 --> 00:10:37.980
undifferentiated public.

00:10:37.980 --> 00:10:42.630
So, stop thinking about platforms and start thinking about membranes

00:10:42.630 --> 00:10:42.940
.

00:10:42.940 --> 00:10:47.920
Living systems maintain boundaries, selectively permeable with consent.

00:10:47.980 --> 00:10:51.920
They signal across those boundaries, not commands, but information that

00:10:51.920 --> 00:10:54.460
others can interpret and respond to in context.

00:10:54.460 --> 00:11:00.090
They adapt through feedback, graduated responses, calibrated to situation

00:11:00.090 --> 00:11:01.500
, not uniform rules from above.

00:11:01.500 --> 00:11:05.340
And they differentiate, becoming this community, with this character,

00:11:05.340 --> 00:11:10.690
with these members, rather than a generic instance of one universal

00:11:10.690 --> 00:11:13.100
social form, one global social graph.

00:11:14.220 --> 00:11:17.920
The opposite of a giant engineered monoculture is not disorder

00:11:17.920 --> 00:11:19.100
, it's ecology.

00:11:19.100 --> 00:11:26.280
Many bounded systems communicating across difference, adapting to local conditions,

00:11:26.280 --> 00:11:28.890
and persisting because they are healthy, not because they are

00:11:28.890 --> 00:11:29.420
controlled.

00:11:29.420 --> 00:11:33.130
So, if that is the vision, many bounded systems communicating

00:11:34.030 --> 00:11:38.140
across difference, adapting locally, what does the infrastructure for that

00:11:38.300 --> 00:11:39.180
actually look like?

00:11:39.180 --> 00:11:41.090
I want to talk about two problems.

00:11:41.900 --> 00:11:44.610
The year before my database class, in the same lecture hall

00:11:44.930 --> 00:11:47.280
, just over there, I learned the old joke that there

00:11:47.280 --> 00:11:50.360
are only two hard problems in computer science: cache invalidation

00:11:50.380 --> 00:11:51.210
and naming things.

00:11:51.340 --> 00:11:56.950
I think that AppProto, and this new thing you

00:11:56.950 --> 00:11:59.810
've probably never heard of, PanProto, between them

00:11:59.810 --> 00:12:00.700
might solve both.

00:12:00.700 --> 00:12:03.410
Let me start with cache invalidation.

00:12:03.660 --> 00:12:07.390
If communities are going to persist, they need durable infrastructure that

00:12:07.390 --> 00:12:10.800
does not depend on one company's continued existence or goodwill

00:12:10.800 --> 00:12:10.940
.

00:12:11.580 --> 00:12:14.710
They need to own their data, they need continuity, memory

00:12:14.710 --> 00:12:16.990
, the ability to move, to fork, to recomb

00:12:16.990 --> 00:12:19.230
ine, and to remain legible to one another through all

00:12:19.380 --> 00:12:19.740
of that.

00:12:19.740 --> 00:12:24.710
AppProto gives us this: identity, data, and

00:12:24.770 --> 00:12:28.080
sync that persist across a distributed network without collapsing back into one

00:12:28.080 --> 00:12:28.620
service.

00:12:28.620 --> 00:12:31.270
Cache invalidation at protocol scale.

00:12:31.980 --> 00:12:36.250
Keeping data consistent, authentic, and verifiable across many independent

00:12:36.580 --> 00:12:39.490
hosts is what AppProto was built to solve.

00:12:39.580 --> 00:12:39.580
We're all building on it.

00:12:39.580 --> 00:12:41.580
You know what it makes possible.

00:12:41.580 --> 00:12:45.770
Now, a question that I find useful is what sort of

00:12:46.190 --> 00:12:48.940
forms does Instagram prescribe?

00:12:48.940 --> 00:12:52.060
That's actually a pretty easy question to answer.

00:12:52.060 --> 00:12:55.900
A feed of images with descriptions that forbid links, stories,

00:12:55.900 --> 00:12:59.340
reels, a specific set of interactions optimized for a specific

00:12:59.340 --> 00:13:00.050
business model.

00:13:00.060 --> 00:13:04.130
You can describe Instagram's social ontology in an afternoon.

00:13:04.140 --> 00:13:08.380
What social forms does AppProto describe?

00:13:08.380 --> 00:13:10.860
That's a categorically harder question.

00:13:10.860 --> 00:13:15.380
That difficulty tells you something about what kind of system AppPr

00:13:15.470 --> 00:13:16.060
oto is.

00:13:16.060 --> 00:13:18.150
AppProto is not socially neutral.

00:13:18.300 --> 00:13:20.300
No substrate is.

00:13:20.300 --> 00:13:23.750
It makes choices about identity, about data ownership, about what

00:13:23.770 --> 00:13:24.300
is public.

00:13:24.300 --> 00:13:27.730
But it's architecturally resistant to prescribing the full shape

00:13:27.750 --> 00:13:28.780
of social life.

00:13:28.780 --> 00:13:32.780
It decomposes what the old platforms had collapsed together.

00:13:32.780 --> 00:13:33.640
It creates room.

00:13:33.660 --> 00:13:36.860
But here's what I think is not yet finished.

00:13:36.860 --> 00:13:39.990
There's the second problem, and I think the harder one

00:13:39.990 --> 00:13:40.130
.

00:13:40.140 --> 00:13:41.340
Naming things.

00:13:41.340 --> 00:13:46.960
I work on a community platform called Roundabout built on App

00:13:46.960 --> 00:13:50.300
Proto, designed as a healthy alternative to local Facebook groups

00:13:50.360 --> 00:13:51.090
and Nextdoor.

00:13:51.100 --> 00:13:54.840
We're currently supporting communities in Richmond, Virginia, Burlington

00:13:54.840 --> 00:13:58.220
, North Carolina, Lancaster, Pennsylvania, Lincoln County,

00:13:58.230 --> 00:14:00.060
Wisconsin, and Chattanooga, Tennessee.

00:14:00.060 --> 00:14:04.380
These are different places with different cultures, different needs, and

00:14:04.670 --> 00:14:07.810
different ideas about what healthy conversation looks like.

00:14:07.820 --> 00:14:11.960
When Richmond says community member, they might mean something different than

00:14:11.960 --> 00:14:13.830
when Burlington says community member.

00:14:13.980 --> 00:14:17.330
When one community says moderation, they might mean graduated, trust

00:14:17.330 --> 00:14:18.300
-building, among neighbors.

00:14:18.300 --> 00:14:21.440
When another says it, they might mean rapid response to harassment

00:14:21.440 --> 00:14:21.650
.

00:14:21.660 --> 00:14:25.120
The words are the same, but the social reality underneath it

00:14:25.180 --> 00:14:25.500
is not.

00:14:25.500 --> 00:14:29.500
If we require every community to use exactly the same schema,

00:14:29.500 --> 00:14:32.620
the same names, the same categories, the same assumptions,

00:14:32.960 --> 00:14:36.280
then we will have rebuilt monoculture at the protocol layer

00:14:36.430 --> 00:14:36.460
.

00:14:36.460 --> 00:14:40.300
We've pushed prescription down into lexicon, we've

00:14:40.300 --> 00:14:42.840
pasteurized the substrate, and built a great, a

00:14:42.840 --> 00:14:46.620
really great distribution system for filtered, normalized culture.

00:14:46.620 --> 00:14:49.250
And this is the problem with naming things.

00:14:49.260 --> 00:14:51.280
Not in the trivial sense, but naming is an act of

00:14:51.280 --> 00:14:52.290
social description.

00:14:52.300 --> 00:14:55.540
It's not in the trivial sense of how communities describe their

00:14:55.540 --> 00:14:59.430
own reality in terms that are locally meaningful and still mutually transl

00:14:59.560 --> 00:15:00.140
atable.

00:15:00.140 --> 00:15:02.790
I've thought about this for a long time.

00:15:02.860 --> 00:15:05.260
It's one of the reasons I was skeptical of earlier attempts

00:15:05.260 --> 00:15:06.780
at interoperable social schemas.

00:15:06.780 --> 00:15:09.490
I didn't think that we had the tools to do schema

00:15:09.810 --> 00:15:13.400
evolution well, to let naming diverge without fragmenting.

00:15:13.420 --> 00:15:15.370
I thought it might be five or ten years away if we

00:15:15.370 --> 00:15:15.980
were lucky.

00:15:17.500 --> 00:15:19.600
After the last couple of weeks, I now think the tools

00:15:19.800 --> 00:15:20.620
are here or very close.

00:15:20.620 --> 00:15:23.330
And that's what we're working on with a project called

00:15:23.650 --> 00:15:24.080
PanProto.

00:15:24.300 --> 00:15:28.700
PanProto is an attempt to create the conditions under which

00:15:28.910 --> 00:15:31.680
schemas can evolve, diverge, and specialize, and

00:15:31.890 --> 00:15:33.420
still remain in relation.

00:15:33.420 --> 00:15:36.660
So that a neighborhood forum and a mutual aid network and an

00:15:36.660 --> 00:15:39.520
art collective can each structure their social life in their own terms

00:15:39.880 --> 00:15:42.060
and still communicate across the differences.

00:15:42.060 --> 00:15:47.330
Not by forcing everyone into one vocabulary, but by making translation

00:15:47.340 --> 00:15:49.430
a first-class property of the infrastructure.

00:15:49.580 --> 00:15:53.810
Not identical, not collapsed into one universal ontology, but

00:15:54.170 --> 00:15:54.850
capable of relation.

00:15:54.860 --> 00:15:59.660
AppProto solves cache and validation, how distributed communities maintain

00:15:59.660 --> 00:16:01.900
continuity and integrity.

00:16:01.900 --> 00:16:05.610
PanProto addresses naming things, how those communities describe themselves

00:16:05.610 --> 00:16:09.070
in terms that can diverge without fragmenting, converging

00:16:09.070 --> 00:16:10.070
, when the time is right.

00:16:10.140 --> 00:16:14.940
Together, they point towards infrastructure that does not prescribe social form

00:16:14.940 --> 00:16:17.970
, but creates the conditions under which many social forms can emerge

00:16:17.980 --> 00:16:20.140
and remain in relation.

00:16:20.140 --> 00:16:21.340
And this is already happening.

00:16:21.340 --> 00:16:25.660
When people in the atmosphere talk about composable moderation, they

00:16:25.900 --> 00:16:27.500
usually mean ozone, the labeling model.

00:16:27.500 --> 00:16:33.820
Label content let users choose how labels affect their experience.

00:16:33.820 --> 00:16:35.530
That is real and valuable.

00:16:35.660 --> 00:16:38.070
BlackSky's recently announced Acorn tool is a beautiful

00:16:38.130 --> 00:16:40.300
and deeply considered approach to moderation.

00:16:40.300 --> 00:16:44.360
At Roundabout, our moderation tool, which we call the

00:16:44.360 --> 00:16:47.260
Empathy Bureau, does not work like Ozone or Ac

00:16:47.260 --> 00:16:47.740
orn.

00:16:47.740 --> 00:16:48.700
It's not label-based.

00:16:48.700 --> 00:16:51.820
It is a different shape entirely, and it's based on

00:16:51.820 --> 00:16:53.900
the pre-moderation pro-social design pattern.

00:16:53.900 --> 00:16:57.350
Like Ozone and Acorn, though, its architecture is

00:16:57.350 --> 00:16:59.820
composable, and we're looking forward to sharing it with

00:16:59.820 --> 00:17:01.400
the wider AppRoto community soon.

00:17:01.420 --> 00:17:05.130
The fact that AppRoto enables all of this without permission

00:17:05.130 --> 00:17:08.140
, without a proposal, without anyone at Blue Sky or the

00:17:08.140 --> 00:17:11.470
IETF deciding it was allowed, that is the point

00:17:11.470 --> 00:17:11.820
.

00:17:11.820 --> 00:17:17.180
This is ecology, ecological computing in practice.

00:17:17.180 --> 00:17:21.100
The protocol didn't prescribe a moderation architecture.

00:17:21.100 --> 00:17:25.020
It created room for moderation architectures to evolve.

00:17:25.020 --> 00:17:28.450
Different communities, different conditions, different forms.

00:17:28.460 --> 00:17:31.660
That is ecology, not engineering.

00:17:31.660 --> 00:17:34.140
And it extends beyond moderation.

00:17:34.140 --> 00:17:36.220
BlackSky, Gander, Rumi, Roundabout

00:17:36.220 --> 00:17:39.770
, we're all working in similar spaces on similar but differently

00:17:40.390 --> 00:17:40.760
shaped projects.

00:17:40.860 --> 00:17:44.010
In a monoculture, that would make us competitors fighting

00:17:44.010 --> 00:17:45.260
for the same users.

00:17:45.260 --> 00:17:48.610
In an ecology, it makes us something else entirely.

00:17:48.620 --> 00:17:52.370
Different organisms in a shared ecosystem, each adapted to our niche

00:17:52.390 --> 00:17:55.340
, each stronger because the others exist.

00:17:55.340 --> 00:17:59.510
We're a kelp forest, not just one kelp

00:17:59.950 --> 00:18:00.220
plant.

00:18:00.220 --> 00:18:05.840
It is critical to our mutual success that we understand this.

00:18:05.980 --> 00:18:06.990
We're not competing.

00:18:07.020 --> 00:18:08.380
We're differentiating.

00:18:08.380 --> 00:18:11.580
And differentiation is how ecosystems become resilient.

00:18:11.580 --> 00:18:15.340
I want to sit with the hard part of this for a

00:18:15.340 --> 00:18:15.900
moment.

00:18:15.900 --> 00:18:18.310
There are many critiques and questions with this line of reasoning

00:18:18.360 --> 00:18:18.530
.

00:18:18.540 --> 00:18:21.170
The one I take most seriously is this: Local self-

00:18:21.520 --> 00:18:24.230
governance has a long history of protecting insiders at the

00:18:24.230 --> 00:18:25.340
expense of outsiders.

00:18:25.340 --> 00:18:30.140
Community standards can mean we've decided this person isn't welcome

00:18:30.140 --> 00:18:31.740
, or this kind of person isn't welcome.

00:18:31.740 --> 00:18:36.710
Graduated sanctions can mean the popular member gets three warnings while

00:18:36.770 --> 00:18:38.780
the newcomer who complains gets shown the door.

00:18:39.820 --> 00:18:42.870
Composable moderation can mean choosing the labeling service that does

00:18:42.870 --> 00:18:45.580
not flag the content that harms people outside your boundaries.

00:18:45.580 --> 00:18:46.860
I know this.

00:18:46.860 --> 00:18:48.360
I work on these problems every day.

00:18:48.380 --> 00:18:50.380
I'm not going to stand here and tell you that the

00:18:50.380 --> 00:18:53.020
ecological model is problem-free.

00:18:53.020 --> 00:18:56.300
But I want to hold that concern next to what came before

00:18:56.300 --> 00:18:56.300
.

00:18:57.420 --> 00:19:00.080
Because the centralized model did not solve the insider-outsider

00:19:00.120 --> 00:19:00.690
problem.

00:19:00.700 --> 00:19:04.770
It was the insider-outsider problem at planetary scale.

00:19:04.780 --> 00:19:09.340
One company's cultural framework shaped by one country's norms applied

00:19:09.390 --> 00:19:12.340
as the default governance layer for billions of people who had no

00:19:12.640 --> 00:19:13.510
voice in its design.

00:19:13.580 --> 00:19:17.720
Rudy's black sky demonstrates this better than anything I could build

00:19:17.720 --> 00:19:18.940
in a slide deck.

00:19:18.940 --> 00:19:23.100
Under Twitter, black users built something extraordinary: black Twitter,

00:19:23.550 --> 00:19:26.110
entirely within and against a system that was not designed for them

00:19:26.110 --> 00:19:28.510
, was not governed by them, and regularly failed them.

00:19:28.540 --> 00:19:32.370
What black sky has that black Twitter never could is self-

00:19:32.370 --> 00:19:35.730
determination at the architectural level, its own moderation, its

00:19:35.730 --> 00:19:37.420
own governance, its own membrane.

00:19:37.420 --> 00:19:40.850
On the other side of the coin, does the ecological model

00:19:40.850 --> 00:19:44.530
also make possible communities that govern themselves badly, though?

00:19:45.180 --> 00:19:48.300
Yes, absolutely, but those failures are local, they're

00:19:48.300 --> 00:19:51.160
bounded, they can be identified, responded to, and rout

00:19:51.160 --> 00:19:52.540
ed around by the rest of the network.

00:19:52.540 --> 00:19:55.430
Under monoculture, when governance fails, it fails for

00:19:55.570 --> 00:19:56.610
everyone at once.

00:19:56.620 --> 00:20:00.440
Under ecology, the network's diversity is itself a form of

00:20:01.210 --> 00:20:01.500
resilience.

00:20:01.500 --> 00:20:05.230
And I want to name one more thing: the ecological model

00:20:05.230 --> 00:20:07.500
carries its own form of privilege.

00:20:07.500 --> 00:20:10.160
The ability to run a community, to moderate, to ste

00:20:10.180 --> 00:20:13.500
ward, to maintain a membrane requires capacity.

00:20:14.220 --> 00:20:17.670
Technical capacity, social capacity, time, these are not equally

00:20:17.670 --> 00:20:19.180
distributed resources.

00:20:19.180 --> 00:20:22.630
A world of self-governing communities is not automatically

00:20:22.760 --> 00:20:23.740
a just world.

00:20:23.740 --> 00:20:27.350
It just has better conditions for justice to emerge, if we

00:20:27.350 --> 00:20:29.010
build with that awareness.

00:20:29.020 --> 00:20:33.150
So the real question is not whether to intervene, but from

00:20:33.580 --> 00:20:35.550
where and with what knowledge.

00:20:35.580 --> 00:20:39.720
The prescriptive approach intervenes from above, with general

00:20:39.720 --> 00:20:41.820
rules applied uniformly.

00:20:41.820 --> 00:20:43.330
It scales and it flattens.

00:20:43.420 --> 00:20:48.530
The descriptive approach intervenes from close, with local knowledge adapted

00:20:48.600 --> 00:20:49.420
to context.

00:20:49.420 --> 00:20:51.590
It's harder, and it is the only thing that I

00:20:51.720 --> 00:20:54.530
have seen that can produce health at the scale and complexity of

00:20:54.650 --> 00:20:55.840
actual human communities.

00:20:55.900 --> 00:20:59.060
Erin Kassane's work on governance in this space bears

00:20:59.060 --> 00:20:59.820
this out.

00:20:59.820 --> 00:21:02.680
The communities doing the best moderation work are not the ones with

00:21:02.710 --> 00:21:04.790
the most sophisticated rule sets.

00:21:05.500 --> 00:21:07.820
They are the ones with the most, the ones most deeply

00:21:07.820 --> 00:21:11.020
embedded in the communities of the people that they serve.

00:21:11.020 --> 00:21:13.680
And yes, in a moment when we're all watching what

00:21:14.050 --> 00:21:18.550
happens with what capital and organizational, when capital and organizational change

00:21:18.550 --> 00:21:21.260
arrive at the doorstep of an ecosystem we care about,

00:21:21.980 --> 00:21:24.710
this is why the substrate matters more than any single company built

00:21:25.010 --> 00:21:25.330
on it.

00:21:25.340 --> 00:21:29.740
An ecosystem is more resilient than any single organism.

00:21:29.740 --> 00:21:33.770
We have an opportunity to break with the world view that shaped

00:21:33.770 --> 00:21:34.700
the last era.

00:21:34.700 --> 00:21:37.820
Not by building a better Twitter, not by building a nicer

00:21:37.820 --> 00:21:42.190
control system, but by building infrastructure that supports many forms of

00:21:42.190 --> 00:21:45.990
community governance, and then doing the much harder, much less

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:49.780
technical work of ensuring that those communities have the capacity and the

00:21:49.780 --> 00:21:51.150
accountability to govern well.

00:21:51.180 --> 00:21:55.020
So I want to end where I started, with cheese.

00:21:55.020 --> 00:21:59.420
The best cheeses in the world are not the ones made

00:21:59.580 --> 00:22:01.620
in sterile labs with standardized cultures.

00:22:01.820 --> 00:22:05.550
They're the ones where someone tended specific conditions in a specific

00:22:06.430 --> 00:22:07.450
place over time.

00:22:09.100 --> 00:22:12.130
They chose the right milk, built the right wooden bucket,

00:22:12.140 --> 00:22:15.780
tended the right cave, trusted the microbial community to do

00:22:15.780 --> 00:22:17.660
what it had been doing for generations.

00:22:17.660 --> 00:22:20.290
They didn't engineer the cheese.

00:22:20.300 --> 00:22:24.360
They cultivated the conditions under which a particular unrepeatable form

00:22:24.360 --> 00:22:25.810
of life could thrive.

00:22:25.820 --> 00:22:31.020
But, and this matters, they did not walk away and

00:22:31.020 --> 00:22:32.350
let nature take its course.

00:22:32.540 --> 00:22:34.940
They showed up every day.

00:22:34.940 --> 00:22:35.950
They turned the wheels.

00:22:35.980 --> 00:22:37.340
They monitored the humidity.

00:22:37.340 --> 00:22:40.450
They knew when something was wrong, before the tests would have

00:22:40.450 --> 00:22:43.120
caught it, because they had built a relationship with the system

00:22:43.330 --> 00:22:43.730
over time.

00:22:43.740 --> 00:22:45.740
That is not hands-off.

00:22:45.740 --> 00:22:47.830
That is the most hands-on thing there is.

00:22:47.980 --> 00:22:49.890
It's just a different kind of hands.

00:22:49.900 --> 00:22:52.620
Not the hands of an engineer building to spec, prescribing

00:22:52.620 --> 00:22:54.380
the shape of a low-poly virtual world.

00:22:54.380 --> 00:22:57.500
The hands of someone tending a living system.

00:22:57.500 --> 00:23:00.210
It's not a metaphor for what we're building.

00:23:00.300 --> 00:23:02.300
It's a description of what we're building.

00:23:02.300 --> 00:23:05.750
We don't need a better machine for managing culture.

00:23:05.820 --> 00:23:09.280
We need better conditions for us all to thrive.

00:23:09.500 --> 00:23:12.870
And then we need to show up every day and tend them

00:23:12.870 --> 00:23:12.960
.

00:23:13.200 --> 00:23:28.860
Thank you.

00:23:28.860 --> 00:23:31.010
Blaine, there are some people who have questions, and

00:23:31.010 --> 00:23:32.300
we have a little bit of time.

00:23:32.860 --> 00:23:35.270
So, I'll run the mic, and you'll answer

00:23:35.310 --> 00:23:36.320
some questions.

00:23:36.560 --> 00:23:41.820
Love it.

00:23:41.820 --> 00:23:42.540
Thank you for talking.

00:23:42.540 --> 00:23:43.400
Thank you.

00:23:43.420 --> 00:23:47.420
Given all of this, do you think traditional text standards bodies

00:23:47.420 --> 00:23:50.540
are still good stewards for the protocol and architecture itself?

00:23:50.540 --> 00:23:59.050
I'm a person to ask about that

00:23:59.130 --> 00:24:00.220
.

00:24:00.220 --> 00:24:03.930
I think we need to recalibrate a whole bunch

00:24:03.930 --> 00:24:05.100
of things.

00:24:05.100 --> 00:24:09.780
So, I cut a piece from the talk talking about DNA

00:24:09.780 --> 00:24:10.210
.

00:24:10.220 --> 00:24:11.960
DNA is a very simple standard.

00:24:11.980 --> 00:24:17.600
There are four bases and a very small number of base pairs

00:24:17.660 --> 00:24:17.660
.

00:24:17.660 --> 00:24:19.660
And from that, all of life.

00:24:19.660 --> 00:24:22.370
And so, I think that's the level that maybe we

00:24:22.400 --> 00:24:25.660
need standardization at, like technical standardization.

00:24:25.660 --> 00:24:28.930
I think app proto is like, you know, the le

00:24:28.930 --> 00:24:33.180
xicons, plus storage, plus communication is like maybe all

00:24:33.310 --> 00:24:33.740
we need.

00:24:33.740 --> 00:24:39.360
And then the way that I kind of think about the governance

00:24:39.490 --> 00:24:41.900
of the next layer up.

00:24:41.900 --> 00:24:45.350
One of the things that I'm excited about this pan proto

00:24:45.350 --> 00:24:49.060
thing is that I think it shifts the conversation to a social

00:24:49.280 --> 00:24:51.260
governance question.

00:24:51.260 --> 00:24:54.460
So, rather than having a bunch of engineers debate about what

00:24:54.460 --> 00:24:58.000
the attribute, what the JSON attribute should be called, we

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:03.340
can debate about how our communities want to collaborate and what the

00:25:03.530 --> 00:25:06.060
meaning that we're communicating across the network is.

00:25:06.060 --> 00:25:10.620
And those are very different people in the room for that.

00:25:10.620 --> 00:25:12.130
So, I don't think the ITF is a suitable

00:25:12.530 --> 00:25:14.460
place for that sort of conversation.

00:25:14.460 --> 00:25:17.820
But I think we'll figure it out.

00:25:19.100 --> 00:25:23.040
I mean, it makes me think about just even having le

00:25:23.710 --> 00:25:28.700
xicons that aren't only defined in English.

00:25:28.700 --> 00:25:31.410
Because maybe it don't matter no more.

00:25:31.500 --> 00:25:34.700
Full emoji lexicons is of course what I mean.

00:25:34.700 --> 00:25:40.320
Other questions for Blaine?

00:25:46.380 --> 00:25:47.180
Please state your name.

00:25:47.180 --> 00:25:48.690
I'm Gav.

00:25:48.940 --> 00:25:49.580
Nice to meet you guys.

00:25:49.580 --> 00:25:54.690
I'm wondering, so what becomes of engineering standard bodies,

00:25:54.700 --> 00:25:56.540
you know, in this world?

00:25:56.540 --> 00:25:59.820
Especially if, you know, like we saw with the Ad

00:25:59.830 --> 00:26:02.140
dy demo, you know, everyone can make their own thing

00:26:02.140 --> 00:26:02.860
, which is great.

00:26:02.860 --> 00:26:03.500
I love that.

00:26:03.500 --> 00:26:06.740
But what becomes of like formal engineering standards, in your opinion

00:26:06.740 --> 00:26:06.930
?

00:26:06.940 --> 00:26:09.650
I mean, I think, you know, I'll kind

00:26:09.760 --> 00:26:13.360
of lean back into that prescriptive, descriptive lens.

00:26:13.420 --> 00:26:18.220
I think that the prescriptive, we're going to

00:26:18.220 --> 00:26:20.970
define the standard, and then we're going to build software

00:26:20.970 --> 00:26:23.420
that conforms to that standard model should go away.

00:26:23.420 --> 00:26:25.390
Like, so it's, you know, sort of Ryan

00:26:25.390 --> 00:26:26.050
's question.

00:26:26.060 --> 00:26:29.770
Like, I don't think that that's a useful mechanism

00:26:29.770 --> 00:26:31.680
in this place.

00:26:31.900 --> 00:26:35.510
I think that there are some really fundamental coordination questions.

00:26:35.580 --> 00:26:38.520
So, like, how do I get data off of a

00:26:38.620 --> 00:26:41.200
PDS is a mechanical question.

00:26:41.420 --> 00:26:44.540
You know, we're talking like tRNA or something.

00:26:44.540 --> 00:26:49.020
It's like these mechanical pieces are important to encode,

00:26:49.150 --> 00:26:52.390
but the rest of it, like everything above that, we

00:26:52.490 --> 00:26:56.620
need to really aggressively think differently about how we approach that.

00:26:56.620 --> 00:26:59.330
And I think really, I would love to see us as

00:26:59.330 --> 00:27:04.540
a community really strongly distance ourselves from this sort of engineering mindset

00:27:04.540 --> 00:27:04.640
.

00:27:04.700 --> 00:27:07.480
And one of the things that I'm really so grateful for

00:27:07.730 --> 00:27:11.500
at this conference is just how many people who aren't engineers

00:27:11.500 --> 00:27:15.820
are in this space, which is a protocol conference.

00:27:15.820 --> 00:27:18.240
And I think that's a really good sign for where the

